 News}}</ref> This is overtaken on April 15 when 2,371 deaths are recorded in a single day, topping 30,800 fatalities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20200415213634-wt4o0|work=Reuters|title=U.S. coronavirus deaths increase by record amount for second straight day - Reuters tally|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[United States presidential primary|Wisconsin primaries]].<ref name=politics/>\n*[[April 8]]\n**Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] suspends his [[Bernie_Sanders_2020_presidential_campaign|presidential campaign]], leaving [[Joe Biden]] as the presumptive Democratic nominee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52219756|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|title=US election 2020: Bernie Sanders suspends presidential campaign|work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/bernie-sanders-drops-out-presidential-race-n1155156|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|title=Bernie Sanders drops out of presidential race|work=NBC News}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: Over 100 inmates at [[Monroe Correctional Complex]] in [[Monroe, Washington]] riot after six inmates test positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/washington/articles/2020-04-09/virus-sparks-prison-riot-hits-more-wa-long-term-care-homes|work=U.S. News|title=Virus Sparks Prison Riot, Hits More WA Long-Term Care Homes|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[April 11]]\n**COVID-19 pandemic: \n***The U.S. becomes the country with the highest number of reported COVID-19 deaths: over 20,000, overtaking [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/04/11/coronavirus-latest-news/|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020|title=Live updates: U.S. coronavirus death toll reaches 20,000, surpassing Italy|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n***For the first time in U.S. history, all 50 states have simultaneous federal major disaster declarations after [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wyoming|Wyoming]] receives the final declaration. [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C.]], the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States Virgin Islands|U.S. Virgin Islands]], the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Northern Mariana Islands|Northern Mariana Islands]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam|Guam]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Puerto Rico|Puerto Rico]] also have major disaster declarations by this time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/11/every-state-in-the-us-is-now-under-a-major-disaster-declaration-amid-coronavirus-pandemic.html|work=CNBC|title=Every US state is now under a major disaster declaration amid coronavirus pandemic|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[April 12]] &ndash; At least 30 people are killed and 1.3 million left without electricity after an [[2020 Easter tornado outbreak|Easter tornado outbreak]] across the South.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://weather.com/storms/tornado/news/2020-04-13-tornadoes-storms-impacts-south-carolina-georgia-mississippi-arkansas|date=13 April 2020|work=The Weather Channel|title=22 Killed as Tornadoes, Storms Tear Across the South; 1.3 Million Without Electricity}}</ref>\n*[[April 14]] &ndash; COVID-19 pandemic: President Trump announces that he will suspend U.S. funding of the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) pending an investigation into its early response to the outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52289056|work=BBC News|title=Coronavirus: US to halt funding to WHO, says Trump|date=15 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[April 15]] &ndash; COVID-19 pandemic: [[Michigan]] Governor [[Gretchen Whitmer]] faces two federal lawsuits accusing her of violating constitutional rights during the state's [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Michigan#Government response|containment efforts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20200416145022-vjhiv|work=Reuters|title=Michigan residents sue Governor Whitmer over coronavirus pandemic orders|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[April 16]] &ndash; \n**COVID-19 pandemic: \n***It is revealed that nearly 22 million Americans have filed for unemployment in a single month due to COVID-19 lock downs, the worst unemployment crisis since the [[Great Depression]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/business/business-news/another-5-million-people-filed-jobless-claims-last-week-bringing-n1185056|title=5 million more people filed jobless claims last week, bringing total to almost 22 million in one month|date=6 April 2020|work=NBC News}}</ref>\n***The Trump administration reveals federal guidelines outlining a three-phased, gradual reopening of schools, commerce, and services for parts of the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/420a38ec14101eab70e07be367ee6422|title=Trump unveils phased approach to reopening economy|date=April 16, 2020|work=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n== Predicted and scheduled events ==\n\n=== April ===\n*April 16 \u2013 Passover (last day)\n*April 17 \u2013 [[Good Friday]] (Eastern)\n*April 23\n**[[Ramadan|Ramadan (first day)]] (Muslim holy month)\n**[[New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival]], part one.<ref name=festivals/>\n*April 26 \u2013 Puerto Rico Democratic primary.<ref name=politics/> Rescheduled from March 29\n*April 28 \u2013 [[New York State Democratic Committee|NY Democratic primary]], primaries in CT, DE, MD, PA, RI.<ref name=politics/>\n*April (''date undefined'') \u2013 Final Democratic Debate.<ref name=politics/>\n\n=== May ===\n*May 2 \u2013 [[2020 Kansas Democratic primary]].<ref name=politics/>\n*May 3 \u2013 New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival, part two.<ref name=festivals/>\n*May 5\n**[[Cinco de Mayo]]\n**[[2020 Indiana Democratic primary]] and Indiana Republican primary.<ref name=politics/>\n*May 7\u20149 \u2013 Wyoming Republican Convention.<ref name=politics/>\n* May 10 \u2013 [[Mother's Day (United States)]]\n*