020 in}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:2020s in the United States]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|United States]]\n[[Category:2020 in North America|United States]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in the United States]]\n[[Category:Contemporary history of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "RopeTricks", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Inter Dominion Hall of Fame", "text_new": "{{Short description|Harness racing recognition organization}}\n\n{{Infobox Museum\n |name        = Inter Dominion Hall of Fame\n |image       = Inter_Dominion_Hall_of_Fame_Logo_File.jpg\n |caption     = \n |coordinates = \n |established = 2005\n |location    = Level 1, 400 Epson Road, Flemington VIC 3031 Australia\n |type        = [[Hall of fame]]\n |publictransit= \n |website     = [http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/ IDHoF]\n}}\n\nThe '''Inter Dominion [[Hall of Fame]]''' is an organization created to recognise and honour those whose achievements have enriched the world of the [[Harness racing]] industry, particularly in the [[Inter Dominion]] series. The hall of fame was created to honor the [[standardbred]] annual races of the [[Inter Dominion]] which includes the [[Inter Dominion Pacing Championship]] and the [[Inter Dominion Trotting Championship]]. The races are held in a rotating cycle in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. The 2020 race is being held in [[New South Wales]].<ref name=\"Home\">{{cite web |title=Home |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2020 New South Wales |url=https://www.harness.org.au/inter/id.htm |website=Inter Dominion Home Page |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe championship is one of the most prominent harness racing series in Australasia. Both the Inter Dominion Harness Racing Council and the Inter Dominion Events Committee participate in organizing the race. Many high calibre standardbred horses have competed in the race. The hall of fame was founded in 2005 to honor the horses, drivers, and other important participants.<ref name=\"Home\" />\n\n== Selection criteria==\nThe IDHOF inducts members based on the following criteria<ref>{{cite web |url= http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/selection-criteria.asp |title= Selection Criteria | website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame | access-date= April 15, 2020}}</ref>:\n\n* Champion Horses :Those with at least two wins in an Inter Dominion series Grand Final.\n* Top Drivers: Those with at least three wins in an Inter Dominion series Grand Final.\n* Significant People:\tThose awarded the Inter Dominion Ern Manea Gold Medal (formerly the Inter Dominion Gold Medal) which is issued for significant long-term contribution.\n\n==Recipients==\n===Champion Horses===\n* [[Beautide]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Superstar Beautide retired |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Beautide-retired |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Blacks A Fake]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Blacks A Fake honoured during competitive race card :: Racing Queensland |url=https://www.racingqueensland.com.au/news-and-guides/july-2018/blacks-a-fake-honoured-during-competitive-race-car |website=Racing Queensland |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Captain Sandy]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Part 96 of a Salute to Trotting |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/PART-96-OF-A-SALUTE-TO-TROTTING-31649 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Gammalite]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The iron horse Gammalite who won 52 races |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/The-iron-horse-Gammalite-who-won-52-races-68806 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Hondo Grattan]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Hondo Grattan - Go Go Go You Little Beauty |url=https://www.johntapp.racing/trots/2019/6/18/hondo-grattan-go-go-go-you-little-beauty |website=John Tapp Racing |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[I Can Doosit]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Interdominion Racing legend I Can Doosit to make special appearance at Auckland's Alexandra Park |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/sport/other/interdominion-racing-legend-can-doosit-make-special-appearance-aucklands-alexandra-park |website=TVNZ |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Im Themightyquinn]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Inductee 2017: Im Themightyquinn |url=https://www.rwwa.com.au/blog/inductee-2017-im-themightyquinn/ |website=Racing & Wagering WA |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |date=March 3, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Our Sir Vancelot]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Inter Dominion - Profile - Our Sir Vancelot NZ |url=http://www.harness.org.au/inter/prof_osv.htm |website=Harness Racing Australia |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Pride of Petite]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shades of Pride of Petite in Auckland win |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Shades-of-Pride-of-Petite-in-Auckland-win |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Scotch Notch]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Scotch Notch sits at the top of this tree of greats |url=https://nationaltrotguide.com.au/scotch-notch-sits-at-the-top-of-this-tree-of-greats/ |website=National Trotguide |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |date=May 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Sundons Gift]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Sundons Gift wins his 4th Grand Prix in a row |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Sundons-Gift-wins-his-4th-Grand-Prix-in-a-row-86099 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Take A Moment]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Take a Moment |url=http://www.classicfamilies.net/HorseDetails.aspx?HorseID=10022163 |website=Classic Families |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n<small>Source:</small><ref>{{cite web |title=Champion Horses |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/champion-horses.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Top Drivers===\n* [[Anthony Butt]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Changing of the guard at Rosati barn |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Changing-of-the-guard-at-Rosati-barn |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Gary Hall Jr. (equestrian)|Gary Hall Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web |title=2019 WA Hall Of Fame #5 - Gary Hall Jnr |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/2019-WA-Hall-Of-Fame-5---Gary-Hall-Jnr |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Brian Hancock (horseman)|Brian Hancock]]<ref name=\"Hancock\">{{cite web |title=Hancock Retires In Style |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/HANCOCK-RETIRES-IN-STYLE-5454 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Tony Herlihy]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Fame - Tony Herlihy MNZM |url=https://www.tac.school.nz/hall-fame-tony-herlihy-mnzm |website=Te Awamutu College |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Gavin Lang (equestrian)|Gavin Lang]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Gavin Lang |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/drivers-gavin-lang.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[John Langdon (driver)|John Langdon]]<ref>{{cite web |title=John Langdon |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/drivers-john-langdon.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Purdon]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Mark Purdon talks his trots life |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Mark-Purdon-talks-his-trots-life |website=Harnesslinks |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Natalie Rasmussen]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Natalie Rasmussen |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/drivers-natalie-rasmussen.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Doody Townley]]<ref>{{cite web |title='Quinn' to create history with Robin Dundee? |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/-Quinn-to-create-history-with-Robin-Dundee-88163 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n<small>Source:</small><ref>{{cite web |title=Top Drivers |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/top-drivers.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Significant People===\n* [[Tony Abell]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Fame - Tony Abell |url=http://www.hof.co.nz/Tony-Abell.aspx |website=Addington Harness Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Graeme Cochran]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Graeme Cochran OBE passes away |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Graeme-Cochran-OBE-passes-away-71592 |website=Harness Link |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ken Dyer (horseman)|Ken Dyer]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Ken Dyer |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/people-ken-dyer.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Brian Hancock (horseman)|Brian Hancock]]<ref name=\"Hancock\" />\n* [[Ern Manea]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. Ern Manea, former president of Australian Harness Racing Council, dies |url=http://ustrottingnews.com/dr-ern-manea-former-president-of-australian-harness-racing-council-dies/ |website=U.S. Trotting News |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Phillips (horseman)|Jack Phillips]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Jack Phillips |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/people-jack-phillips.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Dewar Robertshaw]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Horne and Campbell receive highest honour |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/2014-TAB-COM-AU-Inter-Dominion-Media-Release---Horne-and-Campbell-receive-harness-racing-s-highest-h |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Bruce Skeggs]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Bruce Skeggs |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/people-bruce-skeggs.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n<small>Source:</small><ref>{{cite web |title=Significant People |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/significant-people.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Harness racing]]\n* [[Inter Dominion]]\n\n[[Category:Inter Dominion|Hall of Fame]]\n[[Category:Inter Dominion Hall of Fame|*]]\n[[Category:Horse racing museums and halls of fame]]\n[[Category:Halls of fame in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Halls of fame in Australia]]\n[[Category:Harness racing in Australia]]\n[[Category:Harness racing in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Inter Dominion Hall of Fame horses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Harness racing recognition organization}}\n\n{{Infobox Museum\n |name        = Inter Dominion Hall of Fame\n |image       = Inter_Dominion_Hall_of_Fame_Logo_File.jpg\n |caption     = \n |coordinates = \n |established = 2005\n |location    = Level 1, 400 Epson Road, Flemington VIC 3031 Australia\n |type        = [[Hall of fame]]\n |publictransit= \n |website     = [http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/ IDHoF]\n}}\n\nThe '''Inter Dominion [[Hall of Fame]]''' is an organization created to recognise and honour those whose achievements have enriched the world of the [[Harness racing]] industry, particularly in the [[Inter Dominion]] series. The hall of fame was created to honor the [[standardbred]] annual races of the [[Inter Dominion]] which includes the [[Inter Dominion Pacing Championship]] and the [[Inter Dominion Trotting Championship]]. The races are held in a rotating cycle in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. The 2020 race is being held in [[New South Wales]].<ref name=\"Home\">{{cite web |title=Home |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2020 New South Wales |url=https://www.harness.org.au/inter/id.htm |website=Inter Dominion Home Page |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe championship is one of the most prominent harness racing series in Australasia. Both the Inter Dominion Harness Racing Council and the Inter Dominion Events Committee participate in organizing the race. Many high calibre standardbred horses have competed in the race. The hall of fame was founded in 2005 to honor the horses, drivers, and other important participants.<ref name=\"Home\" />\n\n== Selection criteria==\nThe IDHOF inducts members based on the following criteria<ref>{{cite web |url= http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/selection-criteria.asp |title= Selection Criteria | website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame | access-date= April 15, 2020}}</ref>:\n\n* Champion Horses :Those with at least two wins in an Inter Dominion series Grand Final.\n* Top Drivers: Those with at least three wins in an Inter Dominion series Grand Final.\n* Significant People:\tThose awarded the Inter Dominion Ern Manea Gold Medal (formerly the Inter Dominion Gold Medal) which is issued for significant long-term contribution.\n\n==Recipients==\n===Champion Horses===\n* [[Beautide]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Superstar Beautide retired |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Beautide-retired |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Blacks A Fake]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Blacks A Fake honoured during competitive race card :: Racing Queensland |url=https://www.racingqueensland.com.au/news-and-guides/july-2018/blacks-a-fake-honoured-during-competitive-race-car |website=Racing Queensland |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Captain Sandy]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Part 96 of a Salute to Trotting |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/PART-96-OF-A-SALUTE-TO-TROTTING-31649 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Gammalite]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The iron horse Gammalite who won 52 races |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/The-iron-horse-Gammalite-who-won-52-races-68806 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Hondo Grattan]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Hondo Grattan - Go Go Go You Little Beauty |url=https://www.johntapp.racing/trots/2019/6/18/hondo-grattan-go-go-go-you-little-beauty |website=John Tapp Racing |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[I Can Doosit]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Interdominion Racing legend I Can Doosit to make special appearance at Auckland's Alexandra Park |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/sport/other/interdominion-racing-legend-can-doosit-make-special-appearance-aucklands-alexandra-park |website=TVNZ |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Im Themightyquinn]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Inductee 2017: Im Themightyquinn |url=https://www.rwwa.com.au/blog/inductee-2017-im-themightyquinn/ |website=Racing & Wagering WA |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |date=March 3, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Our Sir Vancelot]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Inter Dominion - Profile - Our Sir Vancelot NZ |url=http://www.harness.org.au/inter/prof_osv.htm |website=Harness Racing Australia |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Pride of Petite]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shades of Pride of Petite in Auckland win |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Shades-of-Pride-of-Petite-in-Auckland-win |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Scotch Notch]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Scotch Notch sits at the top of this tree of greats |url=https://nationaltrotguide.com.au/scotch-notch-sits-at-the-top-of-this-tree-of-greats/ |website=National Trotguide |accessdate=April 15, 2020 |date=May 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Sundons Gift]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Sundons Gift wins his 4th Grand Prix in a row |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Sundons-Gift-wins-his-4th-Grand-Prix-in-a-row-86099 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Take A Moment]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Take a Moment |url=http://www.classicfamilies.net/HorseDetails.aspx?HorseID=10022163 |website=Classic Families |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n<small>Source:</small><ref>{{cite web |title=Champion Horses |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/champion-horses.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Top Drivers===\n* [[Anthony Butt]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Changing of the guard at Rosati barn |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Changing-of-the-guard-at-Rosati-barn |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Gary Hall Jr. (equestrian|Gary Hall Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web |title=2019 WA Hall Of Fame #5 - Gary Hall Jnr |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/2019-WA-Hall-Of-Fame-5---Gary-Hall-Jnr |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Brian Hancock (horseman)|Brian Hancock]]<ref name=\"Hancock\">{{cite web |title=Hancock Retires In Style |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/HANCOCK-RETIRES-IN-STYLE-5454 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Tony Herlihy]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Fame - Tony Herlihy MNZM |url=https://www.tac.school.nz/hall-fame-tony-herlihy-mnzm |website=Te Awamutu College |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Gavin Lang (equestrian|Gavin Lang]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Gavin Lang |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/drivers-gavin-lang.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[John Langdon (driver)|John Langdon]]<ref>{{cite web |title=John Langdon |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/drivers-john-langdon.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Purdon]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Mark Purdon talks his trots life |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Mark-Purdon-talks-his-trots-life |website=Harnesslinks |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Natalie Rasmussen]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Natalie Rasmussen |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/drivers-natalie-rasmussen.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Doody Townley]]<ref>{{cite web |title='Quinn' to create history with Robin Dundee? |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/-Quinn-to-create-history-with-Robin-Dundee-88163 |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n<small>Source:</small><ref>{{cite web |title=Top Drivers |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/top-drivers.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Significant People===\n* [[Tony Abell]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Fame - Tony Abell |url=http://www.hof.co.nz/Tony-Abell.aspx |website=Addington Harness Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Graeme Cochran]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Graeme Cochran OBE passes away |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/Graeme-Cochran-OBE-passes-away-71592 |website=Harness Link |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ken Dyer (horseman)|Ken Dyer]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Ken Dyer |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/people-ken-dyer.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Brian Hancock (horseman)|Brian Hancock]]<ref name=\"Hancock\" />\n* [[Ern Manea]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. Ern Manea, former president of Australian Harness Racing Council, dies |url=http://ustrottingnews.com/dr-ern-manea-former-president-of-australian-harness-racing-council-dies/ |website=U.S. Trotting News |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Phillips (horseman)|Jack Phillips]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Jack Phillips |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/people-jack-phillips.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Dewar Robertshaw]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Horne and Campbell receive highest honour |url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/2014-TAB-COM-AU-Inter-Dominion-Media-Release---Horne-and-Campbell-receive-harness-racing-s-highest-h |website=Harnesslink |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Bruce Skeggs]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Bruce Skeggs |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/people-bruce-skeggs.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n<small>Source:</small><ref>{{cite web |title=Significant People |url=http://interdomhalloffame.com.au/significant-people.asp |website=Inter Dominion Hall of Fame |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Harness racing]]\n* [[Inter Dominion]]\n\n[[Category:Inter Dominion|Hall of Fame]]\n[[Category:Inter Dominion Hall of Fame|*]]\n[[Category:Horse racing museums and halls of fame]]\n[[Category:Halls of fame in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Halls of fame in Australia]]\n[[Category:Harness racing in Australia]]\n[[Category:Harness racing in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Inter Dominion Hall of Fame horses]]\n", "name_user": "Grutness", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecipients", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter_Dominion_Hall_of_Fame"}
{"title_page": "Stone Mountain", "text_new": "{{About|the mountain in the U.S. state of Georgia|the city of the same name|Stone Mountain, Georgia|other uses|Stone Mountain (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Stone Mountain\n| photo = Stone Mountain, the carving, and the Train.jpeg\n| photo_caption = The mountain, [[rock relief]], and train \n| elevation_ft = 1686\n| elevation_ref =\n| prominence_ft = 825\n| prominence_ref =\n| map = USA Georgia\n| location = [[Stone Mountain, Georgia|Stone Mountain, Georgia, United States]]\n| range = \n| coordinates = {{coord|33|48|21.40|N|84|8|43.52|W|type:mountain_region:US_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] Stone Mountain, Georgia\n| first_ascent =\n| easiest_route =\n}}\n'''Stone Mountain''' is a [[quartz monzonite]] dome [[Inselberg|monadnock]] and the site of '''Stone Mountain Park''' near [[Stone Mountain, Georgia]]. At its summit, the [[elevation]] is {{convert|1686|ft}} [[AMSL|above sea level]] and {{convert|825|ft}} above the surrounding area.  Stone Mountain is well known for not only its [[geology]], but also the enormous [[rock relief]] on its north face, the largest [[bas-relief]] in the world.<ref name=GeorgiaGov>\"[http://www.georgia.gov/00/photo_article/0,2091,4802_16275282_27560837_13713914,00.html Stone Mountain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422013135/http://www.georgia.gov/00/photo_article/0%2C2091%2C4802_16275282_27560837_13713914%2C00.html |date=2008-04-22 }}.\" ''georgia.gov,'' retrieved February 2007.</ref> The carving depicts three [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] figures, [[Jefferson Davis]], [[Robert E. Lee]] and [[Thomas J. Jackson|Stonewall Jackson]], and has been the subject of widespread controversy.<ref name=\"Stone Mountain Controversy\">\"Stone Mountain Controversy\" \"[https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/what-will-happen-stone-mountain-americas-largest-confederate-memorial-180964588].\" \"smithsonianmag.com,\" retrieved May 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title=The KKK\u2019s Mount Rushmore: the problem with Stone Mountain\n|first=Khushbu\n|last=Shah\n|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]\n|date=October 24, 2018\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/ng-interactive/2018/oct/24/stone-mountain-is-it-time-to-remove-americas-biggest-confederate-memorial}}</ref>\n\nStone Mountain was once owned by the [[Venable Brothers]]. It was purchased by the State of Georgia in 1958<ref>{{cite book\n|last=Stewart\n|first=Bruce E.\n|contribution=Stone Mountain\n|title=New Georgia Encyclopedia\n|date=31 October 2016\n|accessdate=24 May 2018\n|url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/geography-environment/stone-mountain}}</ref> \"as a memorial to the Confederacy.\"<ref name=Birth>{{cite news\n|title=Birth of an idea: Where the King monument on Stone Mountain came from\n|first=Ernie\n|last=Suggs\n|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]\n|date=January 15, 2017\n|url=https://www.myajc.com/news/local/birth-idea-where-the-king-monument-stone-mountain-came-from/HFpAfVTvdwvTXR4Td6UjHP/#}}</ref> Stone Mountain Park officially opened on April 14, 1965 \u2013 100 years to the day after [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln's assassination]],<ref name=McKinney>{{cite magazine\n|title=Stone Mountain. A Monumental Dilemma\n|first=Debra\n|last=McKinney\n|pages=18\u201322\n|magazine=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]] Intelligence Report\n|date=Spring 2018\n|issue=164}}</ref> although the park had been in use for a few years.<ref>[https://www.stonemountainpark.com/About/History Stone Mountain history]</ref> It is the most visited destination in the state of Georgia.<ref name=Birth />\n\nStone Mountain is more than {{convert|5|miles|0}} in circumference at its base. The summit of the mountain can be reached by a walk-up trail on the west side of the mountain or by the Skyride [[aerial tram]].\n\n==Geology==\n[[File:Back of Stone Mountain Park 2009.jpg|thumb|right|South side of Stone Mountain from the Songbird Habitat and Trail in 2009]]\nStone Mountain is a [[pluton]], a type of [[Igneous rock|igneous]] [[intrusion]]. Primarily composed of [[quartz monzonite]], the dome of Stone Mountain was formed during the formation of the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]] around 300\u2013350 million years ago (during the [[Carboniferous]] period), part of the [[Appalachian Mountains]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?path=/LandResources/Geography/Mountains/SitesandFeatures-1&id=h-2131 |title=New Georgia Encyclopedia: Granite Outcrops |publisher=Georgiaencyclopedia.org |date=2005-01-07 |accessdate=2012-12-18}}</ref> It formed as a result of the upwelling of [[magma]] from within the Earth's [[Crust (geology)|crust]].  This magma solidified to form granite within the crust five to ten miles below the surface.\n\nThe Stone Mountain pluton continues underground {{convert|9|mi|km}} at its longest point into [[Gwinnett County]]. Numerous reference books and Georgia literature have dubbed Stone Mountain as \"the largest exposed piece of granite in the world\".<ref name=\"readersnatural\">{{Cite book|title=Natural Wonders of the World|publisher=Reader's Digest Association, Inc|year=1980|isbn=0-89577-087-3|editor-last=Scheffel|editor-first=Richard L.|location=United States of America|pages=358|quote=|editor-last2=Wernet|editor-first2=Susan J.|via=}}</ref> This misconception is most likely a result of misrepresentation by granite companies and early park administration. Stone Mountain, though often called a pink granite dome, actually ranges in composition from [[quartz monzonite]]<ref>Herrmann, L.A. 1954. Geology of the Stone Mountain-Lithonia District, Georgia. Georgia Geological Survey Bulletin 61. Atlanta, GA.</ref> to granite and [[granodiorite]].<ref>Grant, W.H. 1962. Field excursion, Stone Mountain-Lithonia district. Georgia Geologic Survey Guidebook 2. Atlanta, Georgia</ref>\n\nThe minerals within the rock include [[quartz]], [[plagioclase feldspar]], [[microcline]] and [[muscovite]], with smaller amounts of [[biotite]] and [[tourmaline]]. The tourmaline is mostly black in color, and the majority of it exists as optically continuous skeletal<ref>''Skeletal Tourmaline, Undercooling, and Crystallization History of the Stone Mountain Granite, Georgia, U.S.A.,'' Kristen M. Longfellow and Samuel E. Swanson (incomplete ref)</ref> crystals, but much larger, [[euhedral]] [[Pegmatite|pegmatitic]] tourmaline crystals can also be found in the mountain's numerous, cross-cutting [[felsic]] [[Dike (geology)|dikes]].\nEmbedded in the granite are [[xenolith]]s or pieces of foreign rocks entrained in the magma.\n\nThe granite intruded into the metamorphic rocks of the [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont region]] during the last stages of the [[Alleghenian Orogeny]], which was the time when [[North America]] and [[North Africa]] collided.  Over time, [[erosion]] eventually exposed the present mountain of more resistant igneous rock.  This intrusion of granite also gave rise to [[Panola Mountain]] and Arabia Mountain, both in [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]], smaller outcroppings farther south of Stone Mountain.\n\n==Natural history==\n[[File:Summit of Stone Mountain, Kennesaw Mountain in Background.jpg|thumb|right|Summit of Stone Mountain, [[Kennesaw Mountain]] in background]]\nThe top of the mountain is a landscape of bare rock and rock [[stream pool|pool]]s, and it provides views of the surrounding area including the skyline of [[downtown Atlanta]], often [[Kennesaw Mountain]], and on very clear days even the [[Appalachian Mountains]]. On some days, the top of the mountain is shrouded in a heavy fog, and visibility may be limited to only a few feet.\n\nThe clear freshwater pools on the summit form by rainwater gathering in eroded depressions, and are home to unusual [[clam shrimp]] and [[fairy shrimp]]. The tiny shrimp appear only during the rainy season. Through the process of [[cryptobiosis]], the tiny shrimp eggs (or [[Microbial cyst|cysts]]) can remain dormant for years in the dried out depressions, awaiting favorable conditions. These [[vernal pool]]s are also home to several federally listed rare and endangered plant species, such as black-spored quillwort (''[[Isoetes melanospora]]'') and pool sprite (also called snorkelwort, ''[[Gratiola amphiantha]]'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecos.fws.gov/ecp0/profile/speciesProfile?spcode=Q1ST|title=Species Profile for Little amphianthus (Amphianthus pusillus)|website=ecos.fws.gov|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecos.fws.gov/ecp0/profile/speciesProfile?spcode=S015|title=Species Profile for Black Spored quillwort (Isoetes melanospora)|website=ecos.fws.gov|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Quercus-georgiana.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Leaves of the [[Georgia oak]]]]\nThe mountain's lower slopes are wooded. The rare [[Georgia oak]] was first discovered at the summit, and several specimens can easily be found along the walk-up trail and in the woods around the base of the mountain. In the [[autumn|fall]], the extremely rare Confederate yellow daisy (''[[Helianthus porteri]]'') flowers appear on the mountain, growing in rock crevices and in the large wooded areas. More than 120 wildflowers, most of them native to the Southern Appalachians and including several rare or federally protected species, have been identified on the mountain.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wildflowers of Stone Mountain a field guide|last=Winslett|first=Larry and Julie|publisher=Bright Hawk Press|year=2004|isbn=0-9755633-0-0|location=Dahlonega, Georgia|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Confederate Memorial==\n[[File:Stone Mountain Carving 2.jpg|thumb|Close-up of the memorial]]\n[[File:Stone mountain memorial half dollar commemorative obverse reverse.jpg|thumb|1925 [[Stone Mountain Memorial half dollar|Stone Mountain Memorial Half Dollar (design by Borglum)]]]]\n\nOwned and paid for by the state of Georgia, Stone Mountain is the most-visited tourist attraction in the state.\n\nThe largest [[Relief#Bas-relief or low relief|bas-relief]] sculpture in the world, the Confederate Memorial Carving depicts three Confederate leaders of the Civil War: President [[Jefferson Davis]] and Generals [[Robert E. Lee]] and [[Stonewall Jackson|Thomas J. \"Stonewall\" Jackson]] (and their favorite horses, \"Blackjack\", \"[[Traveller (horse)|Traveller]]\", and \"Little Sorrel\", respectively). The entire carved surface measures {{convert|1.57|acre|m2}}. The carving of the three men towers {{convert|400|ft|m}} above the ground, measures {{convert|76|by|158|ft|m}}, and is recessed {{convert|42|ft|m}} into the mountain. The deepest point of the carving is at Lee's right elbow, which is {{convert|12|ft|m}} into the mountain's surface.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gearthblog.com/blog/archives/2011/08/just_how_big_is_the_stone_mountain.html|title=Just how big is the Stone Mountain sculpture?|last=Mellen |first=Mickey |date=August 19, 2011 |website=Google Earth Blog |access-date=2017-08-25}}</ref>\n\n\"Who first conceived of a Confederate memorial on the side of Stone Mountain has long been a matter of debate..... The written evidence...points to Francis Ticknor, a nineteenth-century physician and poet from [[Jones County, Georgia]]...in an 1869 poem.... William H. Terrell, an Atlanta attorney and son of a Confederate veteran, ...suggested it publicly on May 26, 1914 in an editorial for the ''[[Atlanta Constitution]]''.\"<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|55}} Three weeks later, Georgian [[John Temple Graves]], editor of the ''[[New York American]]'', suggested it should have a {{convert|70|ft}} statue of [[Robert E. Lee]].<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|56}}\n\nThe project was greatly advanced by Mrs. C. Helen Plane,<ref name=\"Emory\">[http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/8zxfs Stone Mountain collection, 1915-1977]. Manuscript Collection No. 95. Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library. Emory University. emory.edu. Retrieved 2017-08-25.</ref> a charter member of the [[United Daughters of the Confederacy]] (UDC) and first president and Honorary Life President of the Georgia State Division.<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|57}} After obtaining the approval of the Georgia UDC, she set up the UDC Stone Mountain Memorial Association. It was she who chose [[Gutzon Borglum]] and invited him to visit the mountain (although, despite his [[Ku Klux Klan]] involvement,<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|79}} she \"would not shake his hand\u2014he was, after all, a Yankee\").<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|58\u201359}} She met him at the Atlanta train station, took him to the family's summer home, Mont Rest, at the foot of the mountain, and introduced him to [[Sam Venable]],<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|59}} also active in the Klan and owner of the mountain.\n\nBorglum's original plan was spectacular: five groups of figures, sixty-five mounted officers representing the states (to be chosen by the states), General [[Nathan Bedford Forrest]] and his cavalry \u2014 some 700 to 1,000 figures, each from {{convert|35|ft}} to {{convert|50|ft}} high. In addition, Borglum planned a room cut {{convert|60|ft}} into the mountain, {{convert|320|ft}} wide, and {{convert|40|ft}} high, faced by 13 columns.<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|59\u201360}}\n\nVenable deeded the north face of the mountain to the UDC in 1916, on condition that it complete a sizeable Civil War monument in 12 years. Finances as well as technical problems slowed progress. The [[US Mint]] issued a 1925 Commemorative silver US half dollar, bearing the words \"Stone Mountain\", as a fundraiser for the monument.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usrarecoininvestments.com/collecting/stone-mountain-halfdollar.htm|title=Information about the Stone Mountain Half Dollar coin|last=Pilitowski|first=Tom|date=|website=U.S. Rare Coin Investments|language=English|access-date=August 23, 2017|id=The authorized issue was 5 million coins, to be sold at $1 each, but only 1.3 million coins released.}}</ref> This issue, which required the approval of both the 1926 Congress and President [[Calvin Coolidge]], was the largest issue of commemorative coins by the U.S. government up to that time.<ref name=Freeman>{{cite book\n|title=Carved in Stone : The History of Stone Mountain\n|first=David B.\n|last=Freeman\n|publisher=[[Mercer University Press]]\n|year=1997\n|isbn=0865545472}}</ref>{{rp|81}}\n\nFinancial conflicts between Borglum and the Association led to his firing in 1925.<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|85}} He destroyed his models, claiming that they were his property, but the Association disagreed and had a warrant issued for his arrest. He was warned of the arrest and narrowly escaped to North Carolina, whose governor, [[Angus Wilton McLean|Angus McLean]], refused to extradite him,<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|89}} though he could not return to Georgia. The affair was highly publicized and there was much discussion and discord, including discord between Sam Venable, the Association, and its president Hollins Randolph.<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|103, 116\u2013119}} The face of Lee that Borglum had partially completed was blasted off the mountain in 1928.<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|111}}\n\nBorglum's next major project was [[Mount Rushmore]].\n\nAfter a number of sculptors turned them down,<ref name=Freeman/>{{rp|97}} [[Augustus Lukeman]] took up the work in 1925, with a different, smaller design. Fundraising was even more difficult after the public debate and name-calling, and work stopped in 1928. In 1941 segregationist Governor [[Eugene Talmadge]] formed the Stone Mountain Memorial Association (SMMA) to continue work on the memorial, but the project was delayed once again by the U.S. entry into World War II (1941\u201345).<ref name=Encycl />\n\nIn response to [[Brown v. Board of Education]] of 1954 and the birth of the [[Civil Rights Movement]], in 1958, at the urging of segregationist Governor [[Marvin Griffin]],<ref name=McKinney />{{rp|21}} the Georgia legislature approved a measure to purchase Stone Mountain at a price of $1.125 million. In 1963 [[Walker Hancock]] was selected to complete the carving, and work began in 1964. The carving was completed by [[Roy Faulkner (sculptor)|Roy Faulkner]], who in 1985 opened the Stone Mountain Carving Museum (now closed) on nearby Memorial Drive commemorating the carving's history.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Stone Mountain's mass appeal also brings some tall problems\n|first=Howard\n|last=Pousner\n|accessdate=May 25, 2018\n|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]\n|date=June 16, 1985\n|url=https://www.ajc.com/entertainment/attractions/stone-mountain-mass-appeal-also-brings-some-tall-problems/KvzUEjSDMfBbchHQfwNoWM/}}</ref> The carving was completed on March 3, 1972.<ref name=SMHistory>{{cite web |url=http://www.stonemountainpark.com/About/History |title=History |publisher=Stone Mountain Park. stonemountainpark.org |accessdate=2017-08-25}}</ref> An extensive archival collection related to the project is now at [[Emory University]], with the bulk of the materials dating from 1915 to 1930; the [[finding aid]] provides a history of the project, and an index of the papers contained in the collection.<ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\nStone Mountain Park officially opened on April 14, 1965 \u2013 100 years to the day after [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln's assassination]].<ref name=McKinney/> Four flags of the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]] are flown.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Flag causes flap at Stone Mountain\n|first=Mark\n|last=Davis\n|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]\n|date=July 2, 2015\n|accessdate=May 25, 2018\n|url=https://www.myajc.com/news/flag-causes-flap-stone-mountain/gzL67vy49V0RZU2yajcnzN/}}</ref> The Stone Mountain Memorial Lawn \"contains...thirteen terraces \u2014 one for each Confederate state.... Each terrace flies the flag that the state flew as member of the Confederacy.\"<ref name=Myajc>{{cite news\n|title=Photos: Confederate memorials in metro Atlanta\n|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]\n|first=Pete\n|last=Corson\n|accessdate=May 25, 2018\n|url=https://www.myajc.com/news/local/photos-confederate-memorials-metro-atlanta/4GRL1pq5JCvgl14heVFn8J/#p4n7UtNgEeaaFysXpM96yA}}</ref>\n\n===Involvement of the Ku Klux Klan===\n\nStone Mountain was \"''the'' sacred site to members of the [[Ku Klux Klan#Second KKK|second]] and [[Ku Klux Klan#Third KKK|third national klans]].\"<ref name=Loewen>{{cite book\n|first=James W.\n|last=Loewen\n|title=Lies Across America:  What our Historic Sites Get Wrong\n|publisher=[[The New Press]]\n|year=1999\n|isbn=1565843444\n|url-access=registration\n|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780965003179\n}}</ref>{{rp|262}}\n\nThe rebirth of the [[Ku Klux Klan]] \u2013 the second Klan \u2014 was inspired by [[D. W. Griffith]]'s 1915 Klan-glorifying film, ''[[The Birth of a Nation]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hartford-hwp.com/archives/45a/316.html |title=A Painful Present as Historians Confront a Nation's Bloody Past |publisher=Hartford-hwp.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-29}}</ref> It was followed in August by the highly publicized [[lynching in the United States|lynching]] of convicted murderer [[Leo Frank]] in nearby [[Marietta, Georgia]]. On November 25 of the same year, [[Thanksgiving Day]], a small group, including fifteen robed and hooded \"charter members\" of the new organization, met at the summit of Stone Mountain to create a new iteration of the Klan. They were led by [[William Joseph Simmons|William J. Simmons]], and included two elderly members of the original Klan. As part of their ceremony, they set up on the summit an altar covered with a flag, opened a Bible, and burned a 16-foot cross.<ref name=McKinney />{{rp|20}}<ref name=\"time\">{{cite news|first=|last=|authorlink=|author=|date=April 9, 1965|title=The Various Shady Lives of the Ku Klux Klan|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,898581,00.html|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|quote=An itinerant Methodist preacher named William Joseph Simmons started up the Klan again in Atlanta in 1915. Simmons, an ascetic-looking man, was a fetishist on fraternal organizations. He was already a \"colonel\" in the Woodmen of the World, but he decided to build an organization all his own. He was an effective speaker, with an affinity for alliteration; he had preached on \"Women, Weddings and Wives,\" \"Red Heads, Dead Heads and No Heads,\" and the \"Kinship of Kourtship and Kissing.\" On Thanksgiving Eve 1915, Simmons took 15 friends to the top of Stone Mountain, near Atlanta, built an altar on which he placed an American flag, a Bible and an unsheathed sword, set fire to a crude wooden cross, muttered a few incantations about a \"practical fraternity among men,\" and declared himself Imperial Wizard of the Invisible Empire of the Knights of the Ku Klux Klan.}}</ref>\n\nStone Mountain was the location of an annual [[Labor Day]] cross-burning ceremony for the next 50 years,<ref>{{cite news\n|title=On Stone Mountain\n|first=Christopher\n|last=Petrella\n|newspaper=[[Boston Review]]\n|date=March 30, 2016\n|url=https://bostonreview.net/us/christopher-petrella-stone-mountain-white-supremacy-modern-democratic-party}}</ref> only ending when the state condemned the property.\n\nFundraising for the monument resumed in 1923. In October of that year, Venable granted the Klan easement with perpetual right to hold celebrations as they desired.<ref>{{cite book|author=Patsy Sims|title=The Klan|url=https://archive.org/details/klan00sims|url-access=registration|year=1996|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0-8131-0887-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/klan00sims/page/247 247]}}</ref> The influence of the UDC continued, in support of Mrs. Plane's vision of a carving explicitly for the purpose of creating a Confederate memorial. She suggested in a letter to the first sculptor, Gutzon Borglum:\n\n{{quote|I feel it is due to the Klan[,] which saved us from Negro dominations [sic] and [[carpetbagger|carpetbag]] rule, that it be immortalized on Stone Mountain. Why not represent a small group of them in their nightly uniform approaching in the distance?<ref name=McKinney />{{rp|21}}<ref name=Encycl>{{cite book\n|title=New Georgia Encyclopedia\n|contribution=Stone Mountain\n|first=Bruce E.\n|last=Stewart\n|year=2004\n|url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/geography-environment/stone-mountain\n|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nThe UDC established the Stone Mountain Confederate Memorial Association (SMCMA) for fundraising and on-site supervision of the project. Venable and Borglum, who were both closely associated with the Klan, arranged to pack the SMCMA with Klan members.<ref name=\"ngeorgia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://ngeorgia.com/ang/Stone_Mountain_Carving |title=Stone Mountain Carving |publisher=Ngeorgia.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-29}}</ref> The SMCMA, along with the United Daughters of the Confederacy, continued fundraising efforts. Of the $250,000 raised, part came from the federal government, which in 1925 issued special [[United States Commemorative Coin|fifty-cent coins]] with the soldiers Robert E. Lee and Stonewall Jackson on them.<ref>Shaff, Howard & Audrey arl Shaff, ''Six Wars at a Time: the life and times of Gutzon Borglum, Sculptor of Mt. Rushmore'', The Center For Western Studies, Sioux Falls, South Dakota, 1985 p. 207</ref>  The image on the verso of the coin was based on \"The Last Meeting of Lee and Jackson\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xroads.virginia.edu/~ug97/stone/coin.html|title=Confederate Half Dollar|website=xroads.virginia.edu|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> executed in 1869 by Everett B. D. Fabrino Julio (American, b. [[St. Helena]] 1843 \u2013 1879, emigrated to US 1860), itself an icon of [[Lost Cause]] mythology; it is now in the [[American Civil War Museum]] (until 2012 the Museum of the Confederacy).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/media_player?mets_filename=evm00001209mets.xml|title=The Last Meeting|website=Encyclopediavirginia.org\\accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> When the state completed the purchase in 1960, it condemned the property to void Venable's agreement to allow the Klan perpetual right to hold meetings on the premises.<ref name=\"ngeorgia.com\"/>\n\n[[File:William-joseph-simmons2.jpg|thumb|175px|[[William Joseph Simmons|William J. Simmons]] founded the reborn Klan atop Stone Mountain in 1915]]\n[[File:19151128AC Klan re-established.jpg|thumb|''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|The Atlanta Constitution]]'' clipping Nov. 28, 1915, describing the Klan re-establishment atop Stone Mountain]]\n\n===Confederate Memorial controversy===\n{{see also|Removal of Confederate monuments and memorials}}\nAfter the [[Charleston church shooting]] in the summer of 2015, Stone Mountain was the subject of a political debate related to the removal of symbols of the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsbtv.com/news/news/local/debate-brewing-over-stone-mountain-parks-confedera/nmnWd/|title=Debate brewing over Stone Mountain Park's Confederate flags|accessdate=2015-08-11}}.</ref> This controversy was stimulated by a movement in other states to remove the [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|Confederate battle flag]] and statues of Confederate leaders from public areas.\n\nA proposal was made to remove the Confederate carving from Stone Mountain Park.<ref>[https://www.rt.com/usa/273721-naacp-georgia-confederate-monument/ \"NAACP calls for removal of giant Confederate carving on Georgia mountainside\"]. Retrieved 2016-07-23.</ref> However, according to Georgia state law, no one is allowed to alter the figures carved upon the stone face. Any changes within the state park would require approval by the state legislature.<ref name=\"carving\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineathens.com/mobile/2015-07-25/removal-confederate-carving-stone-mountain-seen-unlikely|title=The removal of the Confederate carving at Stone Mountain is seen as unlikely|accessdate=2015-07-26}}\"</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 2015, ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' reported the park is considering a proposal of a permanent \"Freedom Bell\" honoring [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] and the line \"Let freedom ring from Stone Mountain of Georgia\" as part of King's \"[[I Have a Dream]]\" speech of 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2015/10/11/a-monument-to-mlk-will-crown-stone-mountain/|title=A monument to MLK will crown Stone Mountain - Political Insider blog|website=Politics.blog.ajc.com|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> The proposed monument is inspired by a bell-ringing ceremony held in 2013 honoring the 50th anniversary of King's speech. It is not supported by the [[NAACP]] or King-founded [[Southern Christian Leadership Conference]] (SCLC), who want the Confederate symbols removed.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Civil rights groups oppose King monument on Stone Mountain\n|first=Ernie\n|last=Suggs\n|url=https://www.myajc.com/news/civil-rights-groups-oppose-king-monument-stone-mountain/iqH55iW9CnU7eiW5oVIWDN/\n|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]\n|date=October 15, 2015\n|accessdate=May 25, 2018}}</ref> [https://www.al.com/news/2015/10/naacp_joins_confederate_groups.html Advance Local] reported in 2015 that both the DeKalb County branch of the NAACP and the Sons of Confederate Veterans were opposed to the bell because it would have been put next to a Confederate monument. Representatives of the NAACP were quoted by the article saying \"It's an attempt to gain support from blacks to keep these racist and demeaning symbols.\"\n\nIn August 2017, after the [[Unite the Right rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]]\u2014a white nationalist protest against the removal of the statues of [[Robert E. Lee]] and General [[Stonewall Jackson]]\u2014turned violent, many people across the country again demanded the removal of many Confederate monuments and memorials as a part of a national political debate.<ref name=\"latimes1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-jindal-monuments-20150814-story.html |title=Jindal seeks to block removal of Confederate monuments in New Orleans |first=Natalie |last=Schachar |date=August 15, 2015 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=August 17, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/08/16/us/confederate-monuments-removed.html |title=Confederate Monuments Are Coming Down Across the United States |first=Chris |last=Kenning |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 15, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-virginia-protests-statues-idUSKCN1AV0XE |title=U.S. cities step up removal of Confederate statues, despite Virginia |date=August 16, 2017 |newspaper=[[Reuters]] }}</ref> Georgia State Representative and Democratic gubernatorial candidate [[Stacey Abrams]] called for the removal, by [[sandblasting]], of Stone Mountain's carving.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/the-week-after-charlottesville-eyes-turn-stone-mountain/kR4u7ofQmbQxF82DrFbmeK/|title=The Week: After Charlottesville, eyes turn to Stone Mountain|last=|first=|date=August 18, 2017|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=2017-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title=In Georgia Governor's Race, a Defining Moment for a Southern State\n|first1=Kevin\n|last1=Sack\n|first2=Alan\n|last2=Blinder\n|date=July 28, 2018\n|newspaper=[[New York Times]]\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/28/us/politics/georgia-governor-race.html}}</ref> She called it \"a blight upon our state\".<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Stone Mountain: The Largest Confederate Monument Problem in the World\n|first=Richard\n|last=Fausset\n|date=October 18, 2018\n|newspaper=[[New York Times]]\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/18/us/stone-mountain-confederate-removal.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|date=October 24, 2018\n|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]\n|title=The KKK\u2019s Mount Rushmore: the problem with Stone Mountain\n|first=Khushbu\n|last=Shah\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/ng-interactive/2018/oct/24/stone-mountain-is-it-time-to-remove-americas-biggest-confederate-memorial}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bulletin 426 Plate XXV A Stone Mountain GA.jpg|thumb|left|Stone Mountain, c. 1910]]\nHuman habitation of Stone Mountain and its surroundings date back into [[prehistory]]. When the mountain was first encountered by [[Europe]]an explorers, its summit was encircled by a rock wall, similar to that still to be found on Georgia's [[Fort Mountain State Park|Fort Mountain]]. The wall is believed to have been built by early [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] inhabitants of the area, although its purpose remains unclear. By the beginning of the 20th century, the wall had disappeared, the rocks having been taken away by early visitors as souvenirs, rolled down the rockface, or removed by the commercial quarrying operation.  The mountain was the eastern end of the Campbellton Trail, a [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] path that ran through what is now the [[Atlanta]] area.\n\t \nEuropeans first learned of the mountain in 1567, when [[Spanish Empire|Spanish]] explorers were told of a mountain farther inland which was \"very high, shining when the sun set like a fire.\"{{explain|date=May 2018}} By this time, the Stone Mountain area was inhabited by the [[Creek (people)|Creek]] and (to a lesser extent) [[Cherokee]] peoples.\n\nIn the early 19th century, the area was known as Rock Mountain.  After the founding of DeKalb County and the [[county seat]] of [[Decatur, Georgia|Decatur]] in 1822, Stone Mountain was a natural recreation area; it was common for young couples on dates to ride to the mountain on horseback. The mountain is easy to climb and there has been a path since the nineteenth century.\n\t \nEntrepreneur Aaron Cloud built a {{convert|165|ft|m}} wooden observation tower at the summit of the mountain in 1838, but it was destroyed by a storm and replaced by a much smaller tower in 1851. Visitors to the mountain would travel to the area by rail and road, and then walk up the {{convert|1.1|mi|km|adj=on}} mountaintop trail to the top, where Cloud also had a restaurant and club.\n\t \nGranite quarrying started at Stone Mountain in the 1830s, but became a major industry following the completion of a railroad spur to the quarry site in 1847. This line was rebuilt by the [[Georgia Railroad]] in 1869. Over the years, Stone Mountain granite was used in many buildings and structures, including the locks of the [[Panama Canal]], the steps to the East Wing of the [[United States Capitol]] and the [[Imperial Hotel, Tokyo|Imperial Hotel]] in Tokyo. In recent years, granite suppliers in Georgia sent stone samples cut from Stone Mountain to the Martin Luther King, Jr. Memorial Foundation to be considered for use in a planned [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Memorial|monument in King's honor]]; the foundation later chose to use granite imported from China.<ref>{{cite news|author=Democracy in America American politics |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2011/08/martin-luther-king |title=Martin Luther King: A blockheaded memorial |newspaper=The Economist |date= August 30, 2011|accessdate=2012-12-18}}</ref> Quarrying during earlier periods also destroyed several spectacular geological features on Stone Mountain, such as the Devil's Crossroads, which was located on top of the mountain.\n\t \nIn 1887 Stone Mountain was purchased for $45,000 by the Venable Brothers of Atlanta, who quarried the mountain for 24 more years, and descendants of the Venable family would retain ownership of the mountain until it was purchased by the State of Georgia in the 1950s.\n\n[[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] mentioned the monument in his 1963 \"I Have a Dream\" speech in Washington, D.C., when he said \"let freedom ring from Stone Mountain of Georgia!\"<ref>{{cite web|last=King|first=Martin Luther, Jr|title=I have a Dream|url=http://avalon.law.yale.edu/20th_century/mlk01.asp|publisher=Lillian Goldman Law Library|accessdate=8 October 2011|date=28 August 1963|quote=let freedom ring from Stone Mountain of Georgia!}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[1996 Summer Olympics]], Stone Mountain Park provided venues for Olympic events in tennis, [[Archery at the 1996 Summer Olympics|archery]] and [[Cycling at the 1996 Summer Olympics|track cycling]].<ref>[http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1996/1996v1.pdf 1996 Summer Olympics official report.] Volume 1. p. 543.</ref><ref>[http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1996/1996v3.pdf 1996 Summer Olympics official report.] Volume 3. pp. 448, 453.</ref> The venues for archery and cycling were temporary and are now part of the songbird and habitat trail.<ref>''Driving Map: Stone Mountain Park'' (2009). Pamphlet. Stone Mountain, Georgia: Stone Mountain Park.</ref>\n\nSome of the outdoor scenes for the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Stranger Things]]'' were filmed in the park.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deepsouthmag.com/2016/07/28/georgia-locations-for-netflixs-stranger-things/ |title=Georgia Locations for Netflix's 'Stranger Things' |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 28, 2016 |website=Deep South Magazine |publisher=Deep South Media |access-date=January 1, 2017 |quote=Georgia's small towns outside of Atlanta, including Douglasville, Conyers, Jackson, Winston and Fayetteville, easily pass for the Midwest, and Jackson's intact downtown isn't a far stretch from 1983 Hawkins on film.}}</ref>\n\n===Aviation incidents===\n[[File:Stone Mountain Grist Mill.jpg|thumb|right|Grist Mill at Stone Mountain]]\n\nAccording to George Weiblen's annotated calendar for Monday, May 7, 1928: \"Mail plane crashed on mountain at 8:00 P.M.\"{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} The pilot, Johnny S. Kytle (1905\u20131931), not only survived the crash, but managed to grab the mail and walk down the mountain.\n\nAround dusk on September 16, 2003, in clear weather, a small airplane circled the mountain five times, crashed headlong into the south side, burst into flames. The pilot was killed. A witness testifying at the [[NTSB]] investigation stated that the pilot, a 69-year-old accountant, had threatened on multiple occasions to commit suicide by flying into the mountain. The official NTSB accident report lists the probable cause as \"The pilot's intentional flight into the ground for the purpose of suicide while impaired by alcohol.\"<ref>NTSB Accident Report: [http://ntsb.gov/ntsb/brief.asp?ev_id=20030922X01565 Stone Mountain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060618142424/http://ntsb.gov/ntsb/brief.asp?ev_id=20030922X01565 |date=2006-06-18 }}, 16 September 2003.</ref>\n\n===Governance===\nStone Mountain Park, which surrounds the Confederate Memorial, is owned by the state of Georgia and managed by the Stone Mountain Memorial Association, a Georgia state authority.  The [[Herschend Family Entertainment Corporation]] currently has a long-term contract to operate park attractions while the Stone Mountain Memorial Association retains ownership and the right to reject any project deemed unfit. Under terms of a 1999 agreement, Norcross, Georgia-based Herschend pays the state of Georgia $11 million annually.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2003/03/31/story5.html|title=New CEO hopes to boost Stone Mountain crowds|last=Woods|first=Walter|date=31 May 2003|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> Stone Mountain Park is the largest attraction operated by privately held Herschend, which also manages several dozen other attractions including Dollywood in Pigeon Forge, Tennessee, and Silver Dollar City in Branson, Missouri. The company's CEO said in a 2012 news interview that the contract to operate Stone Mountain extended another 35 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/business/stone-mountain-park-owner-bigger-than-years-ago/zfETCkZ27Br0r5VgE7vRUL/|title=Stone Mountain Park owner: \u2018We\u2019re 50% bigger than 10 years ago\u2019|last=Bill Hendrick|first=For the AJC|website=ajc|language=English|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n==Places of interest==\n[[File:Stone Mountain Covered Bridge 1.jpg|thumb|Covered bridge at Stone Mountain]]\n[[File:Stone Mountain Railroad, GA.jpg|thumb|Stone Mountain Scenic Railroad depot (1971 photograph)]]\n[[File:Stone Mountain Carillon.jpg|thumb|Carillon at Stone Mountain Park; January 2012]]\n[[File:Stone Mountain Transmitting Tower.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Pavilion and transmitting tower at the summit of Stone Mountain]]\nConfederate Hall, operated directly by the Stone Mountain Memorial Association (SMMA), is a museum that educates students and park guests on the geology and ecology of Stone Mountain as well as historical aspects of the area. A small theater shows a historical documentary about the Civil War in Georgia called ''The Battle for Georgia''.\n\nThe education department is host to thousands of students each school year, teaching the subjects of geology, ecology, and history. Classes are designed to meet the Georgia Performance Standards and the North American Association for Environmental Education guidelines.\n\nThe Antebellum Plantation and Farmyard is an [[open-air museum]] composed of 19 historic buildings, built between 1790 and 1875, which have been re-erected on the site to represent a pre-Civil War Georgia [[Plantation complexes in the Southeastern United States|plantation]]. The historic houses have been furnished with an extensive collection of period furniture and decorations.  The farm features a [[petting zoo]].\n\nA 732-bell [[carillon]] that originated at the [[1964 New York World's Fair]] provides a daily concert.\n\nA [[covered bridge]], dating from 1892, which originally spanned the [[Oconee River]] in [[Athens, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seibert|first1=David|title=Stone Mountain Covered Bridge|url=http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/dekalb/untitled-stone-mountain-covered-bridge|website=GeorgiaInfo: an Online Georgia Almanac|publisher=Digital Library of Georgia|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nA [[grist mill]], dating from 1869 and moved to the park in 1965.\n\n===Broadcast tower===\n[[File:Sm skyride.JPG|left|thumb|The mountain top and Skyride]]\n\nThe short [[broadcasting|broadcast]] [[radio tower|tower]] on the top of the mountain [[transmission (telecommunications)|transmit]]s two [[non-commercial]] stations: [[television station]] [[WGTV]] [[TV channel|TV]] 8, and [[weather radio]] [[radio station|station]] [[KEC80]] on 162.55&nbsp;MHz.  [[FM broadcasting|FM]] [[radio station]] [[WABE (FM)|WABE]] FM 90.1 was located on this tower from 1984 until 2005, when it was required to relocate to accommodate WGTV's digital conversion.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}  [[W266BW]] FM 101.1 now has a [[construction permit|permit]] as well. Atop the tower also sits the [[W4BOC]] [[amateur radio]] [[repeater]], which operates on a frequency of 146.760 [[mhz]].\n\nThe tower is also used for the park's [[Project 25]] two-way radio systems.<ref>[http://wireless2.fcc.gov/UlsApp/UlsSearch/license.jsp?licKey=1302090&__newWindow=false Stone Mountain Park Memorial Association system: WPRF799 (public safety)] FCC website</ref><ref>[http://wireless2.fcc.gov/UlsApp/UlsSearch/license.jsp?licKey=1126604&__newWindow=false: Stone Mountain Park Memorial Association system: WNAU431 (businesses)] FCC website</ref>\n\n===Scenic railroad===\n{{Main|Stone Mountain Scenic Railroad}}\n\n===Stone Mountain trails===\n[[File:Stone mountain walkup 3.jpg|thumb|Stone Mountain walk-up trail]]\n\nWalk Up Trail: A {{convert|1.3|mi|km|adj=on}} trail to the top of Stone Mountain ascending {{convert|786|ft|m|abbr=on}} in elevation to a height of {{convert|1686|ft|m|abbr=on}}. The trail is steep, but spectacular panoramic views and cool winds await hikers at the top.\n\nCherokee Trail: A {{convert|5|mi|km|0|adj=on}} National Recreation Trail, the Cherokee Trail loops around the mountain base, with a mile section going up and over the west side of the mountain (crosses Walk Up Trail). It passes primarily through an oak-hickory forest, but views of the lakes, streams, and mountain are common.<ref>[http://stonemountainpark.com/images/maps/hiking/smp_map_hiking_map.gif ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310191059/http://stonemountainpark.com/images/maps/hiking/smp_map_hiking_map.gif |date=March 10, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nNature Garden Trail: A scenic {{convert|3/4|mi|km}} loop trail through a mature oak-hickory forest community, it is excellent for viewing shade-loving native plants. A small garden with interpretive native plant signs is at the entrance to the trail.\n\nSongbird Habitat Trails: Comprising two loop trails each running {{convert|1|mi|km}}, the field trail is an excellent birding spot and the woodland trail provides shade and numerous native plants. Dogs are not allowed.\n\n===Attractions===\n[[File:Stone mountain riverboat1.jpg|thumb|Stone Mountain riverboat]]\n\nThe park features several attractions that are operated by [[Herschend Family Entertainment Corporation]].\n\nOn summer evenings the mountain hosts the Stone Mountain Laser Show Spectacular, a fireworks and laser light display. The laser light show projects moving images of the Deep South as well as Georgia history onto the Confederate Memorial carving on the side of the mountain. During Memorial Day Weekend of 2011, Stone Mountain unveiled its overhaul of the laser show, dubbed ''Mountainvision''. This incorporates digital projectors, lasers, special effects, and pyrotechnics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/stone-mountain-park-debuts-new-lasershow-spectacular-in-mountainvision-this-summer-118359159.html |title=Stone Mountain Park Debuts New Lasershow Spectacular\u2122 in Mountainvision This Summer \u2013 STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga., March 21, 2011 /PRNewswire/ |publisher=Prnewswire.com |date=2011-03-21 |accessdate=2014-07-29}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Skyride'', a Swiss-built [[Aerial tramway|cable car]] to the summit of the mountain, passes by the carving on the way up.\n\nThe ''Riverboat'' offered a scenic cruise aboard a reproduction of a [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]] [[riverboat]] on 363-acre (147 ha) Stone Mountain Lake. It has been retired.\n\n''Historic Square'' is a collection of historic buildings relocated from around the state of Georgia, including three plantation manor-houses dating from 1794, 1850, and 1845; two slave cabins; a barn; and other outbuildings. The ''Historic Square Farmyard'' features historic breeds of sheep, goats, and pigs.\n\n''Crossroads'' is a recreation of an 1872 southern town with several attractions that include a modern 4-D movie theater, an adventure [[mini-golf]] course, a [[duck tour]] ride. The duck boats have been replaced by the Rockin\u2019 Land and Lake Tour in 2019 due to several deaths in other locations caused by duck boat accidents{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}. The tour includes a ride on a double decker open top bus and a pontoon boat ride at the marina.) stores and restaurants.  Craft demonstrators include [[glass blowing]] and candy-making.\n\nThe ''Dinotorium'' is a children's activity area that features 65 interactive games, climbing structures, trampoline floors, and slides.\n\n''Sky Hike'' is a family ropes adventure course.\n\n''Geyser Towers'' is a playground featuring a large fountain at the entrance.\n\n[[File:Stone Mountain High Resolution Panoramic View.jpg|thumb|800px|center|<center>High Resolution Panoramic View from the Summit of Stone Mountain</center>]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Stone Mountain Memorial half dollar]]\n* [[List of colossal sculpture in situ]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book | 1= | first=Deborah | last=Yost | title=Georgia's Stone Mountain Park | publi